, reinforcing a notion of a rational, mechanistic world that allows for endless progress. In practice, this view has promoted much violence among humans. Basarab Nicolescu heralds a new era, cosmodernity, founded on a contemporary vision of the interaction between science, culture, spirituality, religion, and society. Here, reality is plastic and its people are active participants in the cosmos, and the world is simultaneously knowable and unknowable. Ultimately, every human recognizes his or her face in the face of every other human being, independent of his or her particular religious or philosophical beliefs. Nicolescu notes a new spirituality free of dogmas and looks at quantum physics, literature, theater, and art to reveal the emergence of a newer, cosmodern consciousness.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aComplexity (Philosophy). 0aReality. 0aReligion and science. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy of Science. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Esotericism and Gnosticism. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Religion. 4aScience, Mathematics, and Technology : Science and Society. 7aRELIGION / Religion & Science.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143844965440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438449654423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438449654/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles